                                                        <h4 class="crosshead">âConnect to natureâ</h4><p class="no_name">Green Party leader Eamon Ryan said the government is investing in funds for more walking, cycling facilities and rural greenways to allow people to âconnect to nature in a better wayâ.</p>
                                                        <p class="no_name">He said he would be asking all the local authorities in the coming days and weeks to âseize the moment and bid for some of these funds and the jobs they will bringâ.</p>
                                                        <p class="no_name">He also said there would be upgrades to national parks, nature reserves and heritage and tourism sites. A retrofitting programme would be undertaken, he said, which will be âlabour intensive work â¦ sending a strong signal that it is time to start hiring and training workers in this sector.â</p>
                                                        <p class="no_name">He said it would be a âpractical example of the huge change we will be making as we meet our climate goalsâ.</p>
                                                        <p class="no_name">âOur economy will look different as it recovers, with more work from home, greater digitalisation, and more opportunities to do things differently and creatively,â he said. Adding that there had been much energy and original thinking during the lockdown period.</p>
                                                        <p class="no_name">âWe need that same energy and lateral thinking to fuel our recovery,â he said.</p>
                                                        <p class="no_name">âWe have shown extraordinarily resilience â¦ we can build back greener and better for sake of children communities country and planet.â</p>
                                                        <h4 class="crosshead">CGT change ruled out</h4><p class="no_name">Meanwhile, cuts to Capital Gains Tax will not form part of the Governmentâs â¬7 billion stimulus plan.</p>
                                                        <p class="no_name">Discussions between the coalition parties continued until late last night, but the objections of the Green Party to the proposed cut could not be overcome.</p>
                                                        <p class="no_name">The CGT cut was proposed by the Minister for Finance <a class="search" href="/topics/topics-7.1213540?article=true&amp;tag_person=Paschal+Donohoe">Paschal Donohoe</a> as part of the plan, and was supported by <a class="search" href="/topics/topics-7.1213540?article=true&amp;tag_organisation=Fianna+F%C3%A1il">Fianna FÃ¡il</a> who had first proposed the idea during the general election campaign. However, the Green Party objected to the proposal, according to political sources.</p>
                        <div class="adwrapper">
                <div id='div-gpt-ad-InContent-4' class="ad-inline-article">
                    <script>
                        googletag.cmd.push(function () {
                            googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-InContent-4');
